04332nam a22006855i 9780292784604DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20211994txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927846047 a10.7560/7305952doi  a(DE-B1597)588729  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aPN1993.5.U65bA53 1994 7aPER0100302bisacsh04a384.55/4/0973090451 aAnderson, Christopher, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aHollywood TV :bThe Studio System in the Fifties /cChristopher Anderson. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©1994  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tI. Introduction: Hollywood in the Home -- tII. Thwarted Ambitions in the Studio Era -- tIII. Escape from the Studio System: Independent Producers and Television -- tIV. The Sponsor's Medium: Light's Diamond Jubilee and the Campaign for the Peaceful Atom -- tV. David O. Selznick and the Making of Light's Diamond Jubilee -- tVI. Disneyland -- tVII. Origins of Warner Bros. Television -- tVIII. Negotiating the Television Text: Warner Bros. Presents -- tIX. Reviving the Studio System at Warner Bros. Television -- tX. The Pathology of Mass Production -- tXI. Epilogue -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe 1950s was one of the most turbulent periods in the history of motion pictures and television. During the decade, as Hollywood's most powerful studios and independent producers shifted into TV production, TV replaced film as America's principal postwar culture industry. This pioneering study offers the first thorough exploration of the movie industry's shaping role in the development of television and its narrative forms. Drawing on the archives of Warner Bros. and David O. Selznick Productions and on interviews with participants in both industries, Christopher Anderson demonstrates how the episodic telefilm series, a clear descendant of the feature film, became and has remained the dominant narrative form in prime-time TV. This research suggests that the postwar motion picture industry was less an empire on the verge of ruin—as common wisdom has it—than one struggling under unsettling conditions to redefine its frontiers. Beyond the obvious contribution to film and television studies, these findings add an important chapter to the study of American popular culture of the postwar period.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aHollywood (Los Angeles, Calif.)--History--20th century. 0aMotion picture actors and actresseszUnited Statesy20th century. 0aMotion picture industryzCaliforniazLos AngelesxHistory. 0aMotion picture studioszCaliforniazLos AngelesxHistoryy20th century. 0aMotion picture studioszCaliforniazLos AngelesxHistory. 0aMotion pictures and televisionzUnited States. 0aMotion pictureszCaliforniazLos AngelesxHistory. 0aTelevisionxProduction and directionzUnited States. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Television / History & Criticism.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292784604423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292784604/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK